## Correlations
### Function to calculate Cramr's V
cramers_v <- function(x, y) {
  tbl <- table(x, y)
  chi2 <- chisq.test(tbl, correct = FALSE)$statistic
  n <- sum(tbl)
  phi2 <- chi2 / n
  r <- nrow(tbl) - 1
  k <- ncol(tbl) - 1
  min_rk <- min(r, k)
  v <- sqrt(phi2 / min_rk)
  return(v)
}

### Create an empty matrix to store the results
vars <- names(cate)
n <- length(vars)
cramer_matrix <- matrix(NA, n, n, dimnames = list(vars, vars))

### Calculate Cramr's V for every pair of variables
for (i in 1:n) {
  for (j in 1:n) {
    cramer_matrix[i, j] <- cramers_v(cate[[i]], cate[[j]])
  }
}

### Replace diagonals with 0 for better visualization
diag(cramer_matrix) <- 0

melted_cramer_matrix <- melt(cramer_matrix)

ggplot(melted_cramer_matrix, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", midpoint = 0.5, limit = c(0,1), space = "Lab", name="Cramr's V") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1),
        axis.title = element_blank()) +
  labs(fill = "Cramr's\nV")

  • Theres no missing and duplicate in this dataset. All variables are numeric or factor. Factor variables are summarized in frequency tables. Their correlations were also measured by Cramrs V values and visualized through heatmaps. Since the heatmap of Cramers Value indicated a strong correlation between h_cohort[Cohort of inclusion (1 to 6)] and legume h_legume_preg_Ter[comsumption during pregnancy (times/week)], I removed the h_cohort. Continuous variables are summerized in a large table with mean, std, median and iqr indicating their central tendency and spread.Their correlations were also measured by Pearson correlation mmatrix and visualized through a heatmap.
